# Whitelist, not blacklist — a deliberate safety choice, not a style one.
#
# This tool sits right next to folders full of login tokens and API keys. A blacklist
# ("ignore the secrets") leaks the day someone adds a tool whose secret file we didn't
# predict — and people add their own tools here via programs.conf, so that set is unbounded
# and unknowable. So we flip the default: ignore everything, then allow back only the small,
# fixed set of files that make up the tool itself.
#
# Result: a new secret is ignored automatically. The worst that happens is forgetting to
# allow a legitimate new tool file — which simply won't show up (loud, harmless), never a
# leaked credential. Account folders, deploy.conf, the extracted ma-* engines, and zig
# build leftovers are all ignored for free by rule 1.

# 1. ignore everything, at every level
*

# 2. allow back exactly the tool's own files (anchored to the repo root with a leading /)
!/.gitignore
!/LICENSE
!/README.md
!/launcher.zig
!/build.sh
!/install.sh
!/programs.conf
!/ma
